tary data [Data: Entities (945); Relationships (1706, 1711, 1717)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"DOLLY as Databricks’ open and commercially viable alternative\",\n            \"explanation\": \"DOLLY is a 6-billion parameter instruction-tuned large language model developed by Databricks, Inc., built upon the open-source GPT-J-6B architecture. Unlike many closed commercial models, DOLLY was explicitly designed to show that instruction-following capabilities can be effectively taught using publicly available methods and datasets, challenging assumptions that such performance requires exclusive access to vast proprietary resources. First published in March 2023, DOLLY is notable for being both open and commercially usable, distinguishing it from models like ALPACA that carry non-commercial restrictions. This positions Databricks as a key player in promoting open, enterprise-friendly AI development [Data: Entities (967, 1169); Relationships (1822, 1522)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Shared March 2023 release timeline indicating a pivotal moment in open LLM development\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Both ALPACA and DOLLY were first published in March 2023, marking a coordinated inflection point in the evolution of open, instruction-tuned language models. This simultaneous emergence reflects a broader industry and academic shift toward democratizing access to capable AI systems that can follow human instructions reliably. The timing suggests a responsive research environment where multiple institutions independently pursued similar goals—enhancing model usability through instruction tuning—while differing in licensing and architectural choices. This convergence underscores March 2023 as a landmark month for open LLM innovation [Data: Entities (945, 967, 1114, 1169); Relationships (1717)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"ALPACA’s dependency on Meta’s LLaMA foundation model\",\n            \"explanati